body: Not gonna lie, the fact that the writers see Bucky as a criminal who isn’t guilty enough (bullshit) and therefore deserves to be punished for the trauma he endured makes me a lot less excited to see the new Sam and Bucky show. Like I was thinking “at least I’ll get to see some more Bucky, even if Steve can’t be there with him” and now I’m thinking I’m not gonna like what they do with Bucky and it’s just gonna make this whole situation so much worse

title: Outlaw’s Promise 19/23
body:
Pairing: MC!Single Dad!Clint Barton x Nurse!Reader

Warnings: Language. Stalking. Violence. Law breaking. Minor mentions of child incidents.

You were always trouble. The law was more like a guideline you liked to pick and choose from. But when you met the Outlaw Sinners and their VP Clint Barton. You’re in for so much more. You’re falling fast, his daughter has you wrapped around her finger as well. But when dangers closes in are you saving yourself or can you count on Clint and the Outlaw’s?????

Tag List Is Open!!!

Charlie didn’t announce himself, he ripped open the door to the garage bays. The door slams into the wall, bouncing back, startling the guy under the hood of a car. His head comes up, smashing into the open hood.

“Fuck!” He groans, holding the back of his head. Clint felt for him; he’d been there a few times.

“Punk ass boss bitch in?” Charlie chuckles, it rumbles like an animal in the dark.

“Nah.” The guys older, turning to face them, hand cupping the back of his head. “They took off a while ago.” He mutters. His mechanics shirt says Phil.

“Need you to be straight with me, Phil.” Charlie closes in, backing Phil into the side of the car. “Cause if I feel like you’re holding out on me, I’m going to wail on you.” He growls, Phil swallows hard. “We both know he,” Charlie points a massive finger towards Clint who leans against a jeep in one of the bays. “won’t stop me.” Charlie looks back at Phil. Phil’s eyes cut to him, as if he was asking if it was true.

“You seen those knuckles?” Clint scuffs, folding his arms over his chest. “Fuck no I won’t.” He shakes his head slowly.

“Someone’s stalking my daughter.” Charlie leans in a little closer, he towers over Phil. “Know anything about that?”

“My girl, which means my daughter is at risk.” Clint asks, as Phil twitches looking like he was thinking about lying.

“Hear that, Phil?” Charlie growls. “My daughter and grandbaby.” Clint smirks. “I’d speak loud and clear.” Charlie warns him.

“I don’t know a lot.” Phil trembles under Charlie’s glower. “Just what I overheard.” He admits, looking uncomfortable. “After you left, refusing to give them a line in. Someone dropped a line in their lap.” He sighs. “As a sign of good faith between them, forming a friendship type of bullshit. They offered up some girl.” Phil babbles, Clint’s stomach drops. “She’s a problem for someone but she could be useful, if not they were making jokes about making her a club tart.” Phil spills. Clint’s stomach lurches, Charlie’s fist clenches against the roof of the car.

“Who dropped them a line and the girl?” Clint’s voice is strained, struggling to stay in control of himself.

“Don’t know.” Phil swears. “Just heard the guys while they were smoking.”

“You tell anyone you told us; it’ll be the last thing you ever do.” Charlie warns him.

“Got it.” Phil nods. Charlie and Clint turn leaving the garage bay just as quickly as they came in.

“Where to next?” Charlie asks, swinging his leg over his bike.

“We’re going to meet our procurer.” Clint looks up from his phone, sending off a text.

“For?” Charlie smirks.

“Everything that moves through this town, he has a take in.” Clint shoves his phone into his pocket.

“Where we meeting him?” Charlie nods.

“The Outlaw.” Clint calls as the bikes come to life, loudly.

They sat at a table, backs to the wall, watching, waiting. Clint smirks, sipping from his beer bottle, eyeing the pool table. It’d been a few months since he met Y/N, at the very one.

“You know I met Y/N for the first time over there.” Clint nods, tipping his bottle towards the table.

“Playing pool?” Charlie snorts, looking over at him. “She can’t aim for shit.” He snorts. “But her right hook is a beaut.” Charlie smirks.

“Don’t I know it.” Clint chuckles. The bar door opens, in strolls T’Challa, heading for them.

“What’s the rush, Barton?” He asks, taking a seat.

“Need info, King.” Clint downs another drink.

“Well I am a man of knowledge.” T’Challa smirks. He’s dark skinned, his hair cut short, clean shaven, and dressed like a business man. Except he wasn’t your typical business man, he had a lot of blood on his hands and he was just as criminal as Clint and Charlie.

“Someone is stalking my girl.” Clint lifts a brow.

“That cute nurse?” T’Challa looks surprised. “Told you she was trouble.” He smirks. Charlie snorts.

“We chases down a lead, but I need more info.” He admits.

“What can I do for you?” T’Challa nods, resting his forearms on the table.

“New crew in town, trying to get an in. You heard?” Charlie asks, even T’Challa looked startled by the depth of Charlie’s voice. His eyes flick from Clint to Charlie, a stunned shock in his eyes.

“Yeah, try being me.” Clint lifts a brow, taking another drink. T’Challa nods, blinking a few times.

“Yeah, I heard, punk bitches.” T’Challa mutters. “They wanted an in, but I don’t do business with just anyone. I enjoy not being skinned alive by outlaw bikers.” He admits with a shift.

“So you didn’t give them a line?” Charlie asks, watching T’Challa.

“Hell no.” T’Challa scuffs. “I ain’t risking my ass, my business and my damn life, with you, the Reapers, and the Hounds. Fuck that.” T’Challa shakes his head. He wasn’t wrong, if he out sourced to another, the clubs would want blood for betrayal.

“You know anyone that would?” Charlie asks, finishing his beer.

“Man,” T’Challa sighs, shaking his head “out of the three of you, do you really have to ask that question?” He looks between the two of them.

“Hounds.” Charlie and Clint grumble together.

“Becoming a bottom bitch club to get a line?” Clint shakes his head. “Makes sense, they probably think they can move up, gain more.” He shrugs.

“But if they gave them the line.” Charlie pauses thinking about it. “How did Y/N become a problem for Hounds, that they’re willing to hand her over to their new bitch boys?” He looks over at Clint.

“That’s what you guys have to put together.” T’Challa shrugs. “I’m tapped.” He admits.

“Thanks man.” Clint and T’Challa shake hands, Charlie slips off to speak to Nick behind the bar. “See you soon for a new shipment.” Clint nods.

“Barton,” T’Challa stands, smirking. “what’s with the OG?” He nods towards the bar after Charlie.

“Y/N’s dad.” Clint smirks.

“Aw hell, the towns going to burn down.” T’Challa smirks, shaking his head.

“Need you to be straight with me, Phil.” Charlie closes in, backing Phil into the side of the car. “Cause if I feel like you’re holding out on me, I’m going to wail on you.” He growls, Phil swallows hard. “We both know he,” Charlie points a massive finger towards Clint who leans against a jeep in one of the bays. “won’t stop me.” Charlie looks back at Phil. Phil’s eyes cut to him, as if he was asking if it was true.

“You seen those knuckles?” Clint scuffs, folding his arms over his chest. “Fuck no I won’t.” He shakes his head slowly.

“Someone’s stalking my daughter.” Charlie leans in a little closer, he towers over Phil. “Know anything about that?”

“My girl, which means my daughter is at risk.” Clint asks, as Phil twitches looking like he was thinking about lying.

“Hear that, Phil?” Charlie growls. “My daughter and grandbaby.” Clint smirks. “I’d speak loud and clear.” Charlie warns him.

“I don’t know a lot.” Phil trembles under Charlie’s glower. “Just what I overheard.” He admits, looking uncomfortable. “After you left, refusing to give them a line in. Someone dropped a line in their lap.” He sighs. “As a sign of good faith between them, forming a friendship type of bullshit. They offered up some girl.” Phil babbles, Clint’s stomach drops. “She’s a problem for someone but she could be useful, if not they were making jokes about making her a club tart.” Phil spills. Clint’s stomach lurches, Charlie’s fist clenches against the roof of the car.

“Who dropped them a line and the girl?” Clint’s voice is strained, struggling to stay in control of himself.

“Don’t know.” Phil swears. “Just heard the guys while they were smoking.”

“You tell anyone you told us; it’ll be the last thing you ever do.” Charlie warns him.

“Got it.” Phil nods. Charlie and Clint turn leaving the garage bay just as quickly as they came in.

“Where to next?” Charlie asks, swinging his leg over his bike.

“We’re going to meet our procurer.” Clint looks up from his phone, sending off a text.

“For?” Charlie smirks.

“Everything that moves through this town, he has a take in.” Clint shoves his phone into his pocket.

“Where we meeting him?” Charlie nods.

“The Outlaw.” Clint calls as the bikes come to life, loudly.


————


They sat at a table, backs to the wall, watching, waiting. Clint smirks, sipping from his beer bottle, eyeing the pool table. It’d been a few months since he met Y/N, at the very one.

“You know I met Y/N for the first time over there.” Clint nods, tipping his bottle towards the table.

“Playing pool?” Charlie snorts, looking over at him. “She can’t aim for shit.” He snorts. “But her right hook is a beaut.” Charlie smirks.

“Don’t I know it.” Clint chuckles. The bar door opens, in strolls T’Challa, heading for them.

“What’s the rush, Barton?” He asks, taking a seat.

“Need info, King.” Clint downs another drink.

“Well I am a man of knowledge.” T’Challa smirks. He’s dark skinned, his hair cut short, clean shaven, and dressed like a business man. Except he wasn’t your typical business man, he had a lot of blood on his hands and he was just as criminal as Clint and Charlie.

“Someone is stalking my girl.” Clint lifts a brow.

“That cute nurse?” T’Challa looks surprised. “Told you she was trouble.” He smirks. Charlie snorts.

“We chases down a lead, but I need more info.” He admits.

“What can I do for you?” T’Challa nods, resting his forearms on the table.

“New crew in town, trying to get an in. You heard?” Charlie asks, even T’Challa looked startled by the depth of Charlie’s voice. His eyes flick from Clint to Charlie, a stunned shock in his eyes.

“Yeah, try being me.” Clint lifts a brow, taking another drink. T’Challa nods, blinking a few times.

“Yeah, I heard, punk bitches.” T’Challa mutters. “They wanted an in, but I don’t do business with just anyone. I enjoy not being skinned alive by outlaw bikers.” He admits with a shift.

“So you didn’t give them a line?” Charlie asks, watching T’Challa.

“Hell no.” T’Challa scuffs. “I ain’t risking my ass, my business and my damn life, with you, the Reapers, and the Hounds. Fuck that.” T’Challa shakes his head. He wasn’t wrong, if he out sourced to another, the clubs would want blood for betrayal.

“You know anyone that would?” Charlie asks, finishing his beer.

“Man,” T’Challa sighs, shaking his head “out of the three of you, do you really have to ask that question?” He looks between the two of them.

“Hounds.” Charlie and Clint grumble together.

“Becoming a bottom bitch club to get a line?” Clint shakes his head. “Makes sense, they probably think they can move up, gain more.” He shrugs.

“But if they gave them the line.” Charlie pauses thinking about it. “How did Y/N become a problem for Hounds, that they’re willing to hand her over to their new bitch boys?” He looks over at Clint.

“That’s what you guys have to put together.” T’Challa shrugs. “I’m tapped.” He admits.

“Thanks man.” Clint and T’Challa shake hands, Charlie slips off to speak to Nick behind the bar. “See you soon for a new shipment.” Clint nods.

“Barton,” T’Challa stands, smirking. “what’s with the OG?” He nods towards the bar after Charlie.

“Y/N’s dad.” Clint smirks.

“Aw hell, the towns going to burn down.” T’Challa smirks, shaking his head.

summary: I’m actually not sure exactly how this works, tbh. I remember being confused as to why eScape Tony was drinking. Was that the...
body:
I’m actually not sure exactly how this works, tbh. I remember being confused as to why eScape Tony was drinking. Was that the Motherboard making him do that? Or did Tony want to? Because, if it was the latter, I feel like a better writer would have focused more on the draw and allure of that temptation.

Anyway, I don’t know if next issue will show Tony at a meeting. I hope it does because, as much as I like that Rhodey is here for him, Tony should go to a meeting if he’s worried about relapsing. Which reminds me of how Carol and Tony used to help each other at times like this and I’m sad all over again because, from what I heard, her current writer doesn’t like Tony all that much and we’ve seen how Aaron’s handling their relationship.
